## Plan: Add Pagination to `GET /users`

**Only one file needs to change: `src/routes.ts`.**

### What the codebase looks like today
- `src/data.ts` — 15 hardcoded `User` objects
- `src/routes.ts` — GET /users just does `res.json(users)` (flat array, no pagination)
- `tests/routes.test.ts` — already contains all 4 pagination tests (currently failing) plus the 2 existing `/users/:id` tests

### The change
Replace the GET /users handler body with this logic:

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt((req.query.page  as string) ?? "1",  10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt((req.query.limit as string) ?? "10", 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit); // returns [] when out of range

  res.json({ data, pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages } });
});
```

- `parseInt(...) || default` guards against `NaN` from non-numeric query values
- `Array.slice` naturally returns `[]` for out-of-range pages — no special-case needed
- No new files, imports, or helpers required
- `GET /users/:id` is untouched

### Verification
`npm test` → all 6 tests pass (4 pagination + 2 existing)

